SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I've gone on to Graduate school to become a physician assistant, I work in a hospital with a team of healthcare workers and love what I do. I live with my husband and maybe a few kids, along with some dogs as well. We live in a big house but not too big, with some land near the water. It's peaceful and lovely and I wake up each day happy.
SupportYou_TEXT: Make sure I can get to the first step that is making it to Physician Assistant School and setting me up for success in the program. Give me advice on study habits and courses to take, check up on me in my classes to hold me accountable.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I believe my success in life will be measured by the amount of people I influence in a positive way. I’d hope to be doing conservation work back in Hawaii and I if possible I would love to invent something for the conservation field. I would also have a native garden and be selling plants to local non-profits (and maybe even at supermarkets). I plan to be married to my awesome boyfriend Joshua and live a God-centered life.
SupportYou_TEXT: My biggest worry is that I will be set back by my financial burdens or my lack of life skills. I hope that LC faculty could help me to teach me life skills that high school did not and help me to be a more well rounded person.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: A successful life is a life where I am surrounded by support and feel connected to something bigger than myself. This means being in good terms with my family, knowing and involving myself with my community, and at the end of the day being confident in who I am so I can do those things. Beyond those altruistic feelings of success, I hope to be able to live comfortably and sustainably. I don't want to be rich, but I do hope to be able to not have to worry about money all the time and have the freedom to do fun things. I want a job where I am making a difference and contributing to something bigger than myself. I want to feel useful and busy.
SupportYou_TEXT: I think just being given the opportunity to explore who I am and what my role in the world is will be the biggest help. Building my own confidence in what I believe in and having the education to back that up will give me a backbone that allows me to create my version of success.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am a child psychologist with with two adopted kids and a partner
SupportYou_TEXT: Be nice

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I imagine success as living a happy life that affects others positively. If you can find where what you love and what the world needs intersects, you have achieved success.
SupportYou_TEXT: reasonable assignments and deadlines, socratic seminars and one on one conversations with students to better writing and other academic areas

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I want an intense career. As of right now, I want to be a pediatric surgeon. I want to be busy and well respected within my field. I’d like to live on the West Coast.
SupportYou_TEXT: I want to figure out counseling at L&C, because I probably need it. I need to take advantage of advising, from the pre-med advisor to my own academic advisor. Professors that communicate expectations fully would be very helpful. I think my high school didn’t prepare me for college very well, so easing into things in classes would be nice. I’ll need some visits to the library for this reason.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Well paying job that I enjoy with a good community of friends and family.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be understanding and accessible for any help I may need.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am a successful lawyer who has a nice cozy home.
SupportYou_TEXT: Keep an open door.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'd love to be able to work in urban planning for large American city. I like to look at the world around me and see what can be improved, changed, or removed entirely. I want to be able to change the world around me for the better.
SupportYou_TEXT: I think all I ask is understanding. When I misstep, to see it not as a personal failing, but as a bump on a longer road to success.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am the founder of a technology company that is aiming to better the lives of the underprivileged by providing useful, affordable tech, and also being engaged in political issues of communities around me.
SupportYou_TEXT: Provide guidance and support for me to achieve my goal of becoming an engineer.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am rich and I am doing a job I am excited about, that I love to come to everyday, living somewhere that I love with a lot of friends, and I am making an impact
SupportYou_TEXT: Teach me how to do what I really want to do

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am doing something I enjoy that is creative and am making enough money to live a fun and comfortable life
SupportYou_TEXT: Help me to not fall behind on work

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: At this moment, when I imagine a successful life, I picture community, personal health and well-being, and a career or motive to make me excited to go to work every day. To specify, I believe a circle of close friends, family, and a potential partner would be immensely supportive in creating a successful life. In addition, I picture a successful life as a healthy one, or one in which I feel confident and active. Finally, I'd want a career or job that makes me excited to get up in the morning. I firmly believe in being passionate about your job or finding a job that feels satisfying after you go home every day. Furthermore, I picture myself living in a big city (maybe BC, London, or Sydney), in a lovely apartment, with a potential dog by my side.
SupportYou_TEXT: Coming from a much larger university, I think any and all personal advice or reminders that the faculty is there to help is immensely appreciated. So far, I feel very supported at LC (and I haven't even gotten on campus).

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: In an ideal world I will be living abroad, and working in an artistic career, and will have good friends and a beautiful home in a place I love.
SupportYou_TEXT: Provide me with a healthy amount of educational material, that doesn’t hinder my ability to maintain my mental health, and my extracurricular activities.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Doing enough and being busy enough to support myself while being content. Maybe a family and some friends and hobbies
SupportYou_TEXT: Do what they are paid to do and be underdtsnding and useful

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: i'd be a museum curator for the MFA, or an art historian researching artworks -- either paintings or manuscripts.

Im working either as an independent restorator/conservator or with a museum. I’m able to afford a stable living situation, such as a flat or even a 2 bedroom house. I live in a town that i like, preferably near an ocean. Im financially stable and my student debts are on their way to being paid off.
SupportYou_TEXT: Help me make connections

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I see myself being able to travel to countries of my choice without worrying about financial pressure. I see myself on the path to getting us citizenship and a stable job in the country too. I see myself living in my own apartment that suits my style and personality. I also see myself either on the path or already gotten my masters degree.
SupportYou_TEXT: Help me figure out what I want to major in by having real and honest conversations with me.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Maybe I would be earning a lot on an online job so I can travel a lot or move to a cool spot in the woods or in the mountains.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be happy to assist me if I have questions or need help.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I picture myself being quite financially comfortable with a family, providing thanks to music, full time.
SupportYou_TEXT: Simply help me grow as a musician and learn ways in which to make myself marketable/ other ways to make money off of music

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: In college, I am looking to obtain a clearer idea of the specifics of life after school, but at the moment, my ideal post-school life is built on a balance of adventure (i.e. travel, overall new experiences, being involved in the various communities of the place(s) I reside, etc.) and development of my career. I want to explore the extremes of the outdoors, meet new people, find meaning in my work. My current area of interest is Pre-Law, and I am tentatively planning to go to law school, but I don't know that I necessarily want to practice law. Rather I am interested in using that knowledge to help people in a different way. Potentially I could find an advising position as part of NGO.
SupportYou_TEXT: Coming into college, one of my biggest worries is deadlines. When I returned to in-person school after a year and a half of distance learning, my teachers had significantly altered the way they handled late work in that they would accept assignments without penalty after their respective deadlines. Considering that, I think I would appreciate support on making the transition out of that system and into a system of different expectations surrounding timeliness in college.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Working in a medium-sized corporation with a position somewhat related to international travel/communication or financial advising, and living in a suburban house near a large city.
SupportYou_TEXT: Advising on career ideas and what would be the best way to get there.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I’m not sure how I want my life to look, but I will be satisfied as long as I feel fulfilled. My main goal is to bring joy into the world.
SupportYou_TEXT: Remain open to answering questions and giving advice

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Working in a scientific field and traveling for my job rather than working a desk job.
SupportYou_TEXT: Making sure that I understand the ins and out of campus, and just getting acclimated in general.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I would be an adolescent therapist and I would be able to afford an apartment for me and my partner. I would live somewhere green where it rained a lot, and I would be happy.
SupportYou_TEXT: I do not have the greatest worth ethic and I need people to push me.

LC GPA: No GPA - did not complete first term
SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I want to be living comfortably. I want to be able to visit my family whenever I want without having to worry about financial problems.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be there for me when I’m worried about something, answer my questions in a sincere manner, and just be supportive in general.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: After I’m done with school…I’m hoping to have already moved back to my hometown on the Big Island of Hawaii with a stable occupation, steady income and a happy family.
SupportYou_TEXT: I’d like LC faculty and staff to support me in my future endeavors.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am financially stable and able to provide for myself. I’m living in a big city, hopefully somewhere abroad and climate change hasn’t killed us all hopefully!

A successful life to me means having a good job, financial success, and an enjoyable life. I would like to be doing work that I am truly interested in, potentially in the scientific field, and I hope that I will be comfortable financially and not have to live paycheck to paycheck. I would like to be living in a city, maybe in an apartment, with cats and potentially a partner. I would like to be able to travel, as well as visit my parents occasionally. I hope to be happy and in good physical and mental health.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be aware that many of us haven't had a normal school year in a bit. Be accomodating during the transition from high school to college. Try to get to know individual students, even with the current large enrollment. SuccessfulLife_TEXT: A large house, my family, a child or two, a successful teaching or tutoring career. or, even more ideal- working from home as a novelist.
SupportYou_TEXT: Connect me with more writing workshops/resources for amateur writers

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I imagine my life to be successful if I am working at a stable job and not worrying about when my next paycheck is. I want to live on the east coast and have friends who love me.
SupportYou_TEXT: I believe if the staff supports me through hard times I will be able to become successful.

CollGoals_Other_TEXT: I want to be able to feel good about myself and be able to look back on the things that I have done and be proud.
SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Ever since I was like 4 I have been manifesting that I will become extremely rich so I will be able to give money back to my community and other communities. As I've gotten older I have realized that being physically rich is in-fact one of my goals but also to actually have a rich life as well. To me that means that I like the job I have, I am not also worrying about something or someone, I feel like I can take time off when I need to, have a roof over my head, and be able to fill the table with whatever foods I want. In the future I probably want a wife but not for a while, and after working at summer camps for like 4 years I am not sure that I want kids. Maybe I just want to be one of those really dope uncles. But yeah I pretty much want to be living the life of luxury and still be able to give back to the world.
SupportYou_TEXT: I am a really stubborn person and also procrastinate a lot. So I think I will probably want a few tutors or something if that is possible. I'm gonna try to make some study groups because that sounds fun but mostly I think that I will just need help academically.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I’m going to be a successful doctor in whatever field I chose to pursue and I will be financially stable enough to support the lifestyle I want to be able to have.
SupportYou_TEXT: Clear communication and patience are all I need in order to work through problems and succeed

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'd like to see myself living in an apartment in Portland with a stable job in which I feel like I'm making an impact.
SupportYou_TEXT: I think generally just being supportive and open.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT:
I see myself living in the PNW after graduating, and possibly moving to another country. I hope to be surrounded by good friends while still having the time and money to visit my family often and travel. I would love to work with an organization that focuses on sustainability specifically with food security, farming, and cooking or design like landscape architecture. Some of the most important parts of my future career are that I get hands-on experience where I'm not going to an office every day, I learn from and enjoy the people I work with, and I feel happy about the work I'm doing. 
It's also a dream of mine to play music wherever I'm living whether that's being on the sub list for the city orchestra, or playing gigs for pit orchestras or other fun types of music. Right now, I'd love to see myself in a bluegrass band in or after college. 
I hope to at some point be able to have a place to live where I can have a garden and a cat. :)
SupportYou_TEXT:
I'd like to be as informed as I can be about opportunities to try things outside of L&C like internships. So if my music and environmental studies professors know of ways to explore those fields in Portland or can recommend things for me to get involved with that would be great.
It's also been extremely helpful to me in the past when teachers or advisors have shared their knowledge and experience about what kinds of things you can do with a certain degree or the things you can/will do in a certain career/field.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Participating in a community where I feel valued, creating change even if it is small, surrounded by people who I care about and love.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be there to listen and give feedback about triumphs and struggles both academic and non.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am a psychiatrist and had opened up my personal clinic for the lower class.
SupportYou_TEXT: Answer any questions we have during office hours

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I want to start a family with my current girlfriend and build a life together. Financial literacy and freedom have always been things I wish to strive in and I plan do that in and after college.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be understanding that we are still kids but also push us to be the best version of ourselves, not the best possible students.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Right now my idea of my future is working as a general surgeon. I want to be able to support myself financially with a house or an apartment in Portland with two cats. I travel often sometimes for work and sometimes on vacation. My job challenges me and I am able to continue learning new things even though I am no longer in school. In my free time, I read lots and on the weekends I go out dancing with friends. I talk to my family often and cherish spending time with my siblings and parents for holidays and birthdays and sometimes just to get brunch and catch up. I have friends all around the world from my many trips and when I feel the need to take a step back from my work I plan trips to see them to catch up and surround myself with different cultures.
SupportYou_TEXT: Have patience and grace as I navigate living on my own for the first time and being willing to listen when I reach out for help.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I have a stable job working with animals. I am able to live comfortably, without much worry of money. I have an active social life with plenty of time for relaxation.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be approachable.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: If I truly enjoy computer science and see it as something I want to impact the world with then I see myself working as a web developer for Spotify I guess! This would be after grad school I would think. I would be living in New York, a place I've always wanted to check out and see what life is like there, in a studio apartment going out at night with friends. I guess this basically motions toward the fact that I haven't given it much thought!
SupportYou_TEXT: To be completely honest coming into college life at L&C I don't have any ideas for the staff and faculty to help me. The only thing I could say is that it would probably mean the world to have someone to go and talk to if I'm struggling with scheduling or managing my time in order to complete quality work on time.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I would hope to enjoy my job and make enough to support myself comfortably while building my savings.
SupportYou_TEXT: Show how the things I learn would be helpful in the real world.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Pursuing higher education (maybe law school), having the means to financial support myself, and having time to give back to family and friends (and go traveling).
SupportYou_TEXT: Directing me to the proper resources and faculty to talk to when I am in need of specific support.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: success to me looks like being able to be outside as much as possible, i want to live an outdoorsy lifestyle and have community with those around me. this is a big question however and im not really sure about other specifics. i want to be able to cook for myself and friends and family. and i want to be a leader of some sort.
SupportYou_TEXT: firstly i think to support my ADHD with accomodations and whatnot. And having class outdide would be really cool sometimes too.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am in a health long-term relationship, I own/rent a nice house or apartment comfortably, I have my masters in education and am teaching in an IB program at a high school in Oregon, Washington, or California, I have two dogs and am able to give them pampered lives, I am not worried about mental health issues or money

I’ve started my career as a high school theatre teacher and I’ve established enough income to buy a house. I’m working all day everyday to give my students the opportunities they deserve and then coming home to a supportive wife who is patient with me. I’m a bit all over the place, but I’m level headed. I know what I’ve gotta do. Then I can finally rest.
SupportYou_TEXT: Just be patient and understanding that college is probably hard and it can be draining. That life isn’t always great and things happen. Just pick up on social cues if I’m having a hard time!

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: A job that I am excited to go to everyday and that supports me financially. hopefully living by the beach somewhere

SupportYou_TEXT: Provide a solid platform for me to launch into the rest of my studies.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'd like to imagine that I'll live in a nice city that I enjoy and have a career that truly relies on me or that I make a difference to/possibly lead. I'd hope that both my career and personal life are social and I keep important people close to me without worry.
SupportYou_TEXT: I'm not particularly worried about this, but as long as there are clear options and opportunities with clear ways to partake in them, I'll be happy and less overwhelmed.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I want to be passionate and engaged in whatever career Im involved in. I want to be traveling and having meaningful experiences that further my research and passions.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: doing what I love and enjoying it

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I have at least a masters in psych and I’m working to pursue forensic psychology. I want to build a home for myself out of shopping containers and have learned how to weld to I can help build it. I want plants everywhere in my home, an orchard in the back, a herd of deer in a pasture, and a vegetable, herb, and tea garden. I want to do ceramics, glass blowing, wood working, jewelry-making, and paper crafts. I want to be a foster mom, and maybe have 1-3 of my own. I’d like my home to be a space for people who need a place to stay until they can get on their feet again (financially) as well. They would help me run a soup kitchen or farmers market out of my backyard and their time would be their rent, but we’d still help them get a job. I want to be able to earn enough money to start a Roth IRA for each of my foster kids so they can get the education they deserve and I hope I’m well traveled. I also have to have at least one cat, a dog, maybe a goat, who knows :)
SupportYou_TEXT: I naturally don’t speak unless spoken to, but I almost always have something to say. I love to have meaningful and deep debates, so calling me out and asking the hard questions is the best way to keep me engaged. I like to work with the intangibles of life and the philosophy of it.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am living comfortably in a home that I was able to purchase because of my dedication to my job that I genuinely enjoy. I hope that I have put myself in many uncomfortable situations to lead me on my path towards success.

I want to move towards becoming a psychologist; maybe even a psychiatrist. I am specifically interested in psychiatric medication and how it affects different kinds of people. Going to graduate school would be amazing, but it will be a challenge. I plan to pay graduate school completely on my own and feel like I have earned it. I imagine myself helping develop new drugs with that would play niche roles in helping people with very specific conditions, like comorbid disorders that require specialized care.
SupportYou_TEXT: I would like guidance on what courses to take that will lead me to that path. Have conversation about what requirements I need to eventually work with substances. I know it is a little bit of a different path because, although I find it interesting, I am unsure about being a therapist and working with patients.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: In an ideal world after college I would be in a career that makes me happy.  It doesn't necessarily have to make the most money but I hope it will work towards things I'm passionate about, (helping people, animals, the environment, etc.).  I hope to have time to travel and explore the world.  I hope to be happy with myself and the relationships I've built around my life.  I would love to have a cat or dog too.
SupportYou_TEXT: I guess just providing support in and away from the classroom, as well as being enthusiastic about what they are teaching.  I find that I enjoy learning something new so much more when the professor is excited to teach it.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'd like to be a therapist. Ideally I'd be making the dystopian American medical support network a little less dystopian. I'd like to still be close with any friends and not be living pay-check to pay-check
SupportYou_TEXT: Going into how to achieve that career path with advisors and whatnot would be ideal.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I see myself as a successful scientist. I have a large terrarium at home and I am engaged in breeding a variety of insects and reptiles. I work mainly with animals in environmental protection.
SupportYou_TEXT: I think we should listen to each other and help when it’s necessary. Also trust each other and be respectful.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am helping others. Maybe that is being a UN journalist and using my platform to bring awareness to critical topics, maybe that is being back home and working in my local government, or maybe using my love for writing to tell peoples stories.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be willing to allow for mental health concerns granted how stressed we've all been recently.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'm helping people around the world
SupportYou_TEXT: connect me with internships

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Playing basketball in the WNBA and starting my own business of designing shoes for Nike. Living in an apartment or possibly a house.
SupportYou_TEXT: Having multiple options of help with tutoring and such like that.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I'm not really 100% sure about what I want to do, but maybe I'd be a teacher or a professor.
I want to continue learning my whole life, and work in a job where I can help people, even if it's on a small scale. I want to explore different things and avoid getting stuck in one job forever.
SupportYou_TEXT: I want the LC class to support me in exploring different classes and taking my time in declaring a major

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: At some point in my life, I'd love to have everyone I care for in a ballroom in a building that I own. What the occasion is could be anything, from a company party, a wedding, a baby shower, anything that has something to do either monetary success, or family success. Honestly, I rather it be something to do with starting a family, because to me, starting my own family is something very important to me and I will only want to raise a kid when I know I am in a position where I can take care of my family comfortably and provide them the best life I can.
SupportYou_TEXT: I'd love to just have the time to meet the people. Everyone has a story and something to learn. I didn't just sign up to LC for the academics (although it was a primary point), but for the community and the connections I can build. Coming from a small school, I connect with my teachers to a personal level and through that I learned a lot more. That is something that would help me not only be a better student, but a better person in the long run.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I have a job that I enjoy and to be helping people to the best of my ability.
SupportYou_TEXT: To be welcoming.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I’d have a lot of different job and life experiences behind me and I’d have a stable job that I love. Maybe doing research in psychology, biology, or basically anything, or I’d run a business. I’d have my own home but I’d also own vacation houses all over the world that I’d spend a majority of my time in.
SupportYou_TEXT: Provide me with information about learning/job opportunities both on and outside of campus

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Really my ultimate goals have to do with being able to facilitate travel and experience of different cultures and countries either through my work or by means of the money I'm making from work. Right now I am really interested in working as a teacher in a foreign country as a means to start this process after university.
SupportYou_TEXT: Continue to support me in the way that they already have, and aid me in navigating my way to a proper graduation.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I imagine living with some friends in an apartment back home in Phoenix. I’m not sure what kind of job I’ll have quite yet.
SupportYou_TEXT: Be there for students when they need someone to talk to.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I want to be working in the scientific field, perhaps as a biotechnologist or biomedical scientist. I want to be able to support myself and a family and live a life where I am able to do things that bring me joy.
SupportYou_TEXT: I guess what I want, which is already available, is having resources available to help when I am struggling in a class so that I am able to successfully learn the material.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am financially independent living in Oregon with a good paying job that has something to do with film and art. I’m traveling a little bit but I’m living my life to the fullest.
SupportYou_TEXT: They could help me navigate the classes I need to take in order to be successful and graduate.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am a homeowner who’s financially secure and I have a job I love. I’m also involved in my community and social justice orgs. I have a good circle of friends.
SupportYou_TEXT: Ensure that there are more open choices for classes so I can take courses I’m interested in that will help me decide on a major.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I would love to have a family and enough money to buy a house. I want to be able to retire in my late 50s. I hope that my job leaves a good impact on the planet.
SupportYou_TEXT: The most I can hope for is having the guidance I need to find what I am passionate about at LC and help building connections for a successful career.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Once I am done nigh all of my schooling, I hope to have gotten my medical degree and be working as a physician and doing research medicine to help make a positive impact on the world and in people’s lives. I hope to also be financially stable and eventually have a house and a family in the future.
SupportYou_TEXT: It would be helpful if the faculty and staff helped me prepare for medical school and show me the steps I can take now in order to work towards this goal.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Having a job that is engaging enough to not be terribly bored and sustainable for my physical/mental health, and making enough money to be able to live comfortably (in the sense of being able to afford rent, food etc). Ideally having some amount of extra time and/or money beyond that to be able to put towards social activism work/give back to the community in some way. Currently I’m thinking I might be interested in working in some sort of healthcare-adjacent field (like community public health), but I know my specific ideas about what I want to do will probably change a lot throughout college and beyond.
SupportYou_TEXT: My biggest concern going into this year is balancing academics and college life with taking care of myself physically and mentally, especially around some chronic medical issues I’ve been dealing with. I think it’s helpful for faculty and staff to just be aware of this. A more specific thing that is often helpful for me is talking through time management and breaking down bigger assignments, as well as talking about class material in more detail on-on-one.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I’m going to be a successful doctor working at the hospital that I’ve been an intern at for two years now
SupportYou_TEXT: Talk about opportunities to further my medical knowledge in Portland (internships, research, etc)

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am a home owner. I have a career possibly doing scientific research of some kind (I’m not really sure what I want to do yet though). I want to live comfortably enough for money to not be a source of stress in my life.
SupportYou_TEXT: Help me make a 4 year plan for college. I want to go abroad one semester and possibly graduate a semester early. Is there a support center that can help with financial affairs like taxes?

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I will hopefully be traveling, but whether I am at home or abroad I will be learning new things everyday. I will make time for myself and my family & friends. I will be active physically, and grounded mentally. I will cook for myself and those I love--set the table, play some music. I will be outgoing and inviting people into my life with an open heart. I will sleep with the windows open in the summertime knowing that I am safe and loved by the oneness.
SupportYou_TEXT: I think LC faculty and staff need to be sympathetic towards the fact that none of us have been in a real academic environment for a while. They need to be kind to themselves and to the students. For me in particular, I think that it would be helpful for faculty & staff to keep in mind that I have not been in school for a while and be forgiving when my mind wanders, I need extra time, or I ask "stupid" questions.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I hope I can afford a house and that I will be with the people I love. I hope to work a job where I give back to my hometown or surrounding communities to make it better for the next generation. SuccessfulLife_TEXT:
In an ideal world, I would be a successful narrative designer in the video game industry, living in the Pacific Northwest with my partner and a cat or two. We live within walking distance of a farmer's market and several restaurants. We have enough money to eat out when we want, but we cook together when we can, and ramble about our various creative writing projects over the dinner table. Although I love my professional work, I still have time to write for myself.

I also call my parents once a week. My brother and I have plans to take them abroad over the summer. (They've always wanted to travel outside the country, but never had the money.) Planes still worry me a bit, but I'm being treated for my migraines, and they don't impact my life like they used to. I got a hysterectomy. I meet with my therapist once or twice a month. My partner and I host regular game nights with our friends, which sometimes turn into movie nights. I keep up to date on climate change research. I champion quality representation in the gaming industry, both on and behind the screen, and accessible mental health services in the broader public. I call my brother before every election to go through the candidates.

The world is probably still on fire. I'm still afraid to walk home alone at night. I still have mornings when I don't want to get out of bed. I still make sure my partner eats and takes their meds. I still read headlines about mass shootings. On my bad days, I still feel insufficient and petty and helpless and nihilistic.

On my good days, I think: "We're still here. And I'm glad."
SupportYou_TEXT: I will no doubt need academic and emotional support throughout the year, but I know where to find you all! As long as you keep your doors open, I will consider myself supported. (And thank you in advance.)

SuccessfulLife_TEXT:
Above all the other, smaller hopes and intentions I have for my life, my greatest ambitions are these: to do everything I can to create a life in which I am happy, and to live my life in a way that matters. 
In terms of the first, I'm not a particularly optimistic person, by nature. I don't have any particular illusions that growing up and living life is an inherently and frequently joyful experience. There was, though, a quote I read once, that, paraphrased, said this: that the best one can hope for is that an average, normal child will grow into an average, mildly contented adult. This idea -- that the best outcome of the human condition is "mildly contented" -- is something that I not only find myself unable to accept, but which I also find upsetting and distressing. I don't expect my life to be constantly joyful, but I do intend to navigate it not by tolerating it, but by experiencing it, and all the turbulence and emotion that accompanies it. I might be angry, or excited, or nervous, or at ease, but one of my biggest hopes for my life going forward is that, when it comes to an end, I will be able to look back and summarize my life, and that when a hundred words come forward to express a million tiny memories, the words "mild" or "content" will not be among them. 
As for the second, one of the biggest lessons my family has passed to me is that if you can do something to help a situation in need of it, it is, to an extent, a responsibility to do what you can for it. My parents might not be Spider-Man, despite this dogma, but the cause they and much of the rest of my family has chosen to fight for has been conservation. I grew up surrounded by the tangible progress my parents and grandparents made in California and beyond preserving nature for generations to come and slowing down the long-term damage which has been so prevalent recently in climate reports and press releases. I have always been deeply inspired by what they do and how they chose to spend their lives, and though I don't know yet in what arena I would like to practice it, I intend to follow in their footsteps and use my life to make a difference, in whatever way I can.
Finally, aside from these large and somewhat vague ambitions, I have a thousand smaller hopes and dreams. Some of these are: having a home in the woods, and adopting a pack of dogs to keep me company there; writing and publishing a fiction novel; try a dragonfruit; learn to sailboard; and maybe even, after all these years, learn how to make a functional gluten free pie crust, to serve my mom at Thanksgiving.
SupportYou_TEXT: The most helpful way L&C may be able to support me this has to do with the migraines I get frequently. I hope to establish a 504 plan with the office of student accessibility, so that I might be able to receive certain accommodations for moments when my physical health compromises my ability to attend class or complete work as quickly as I might otherwise be able to.

SupportYou_TEXT: Faculty and staff at LC can support me by being understanding of the stress that comes not only with college but also being in school for the first time really in over a year and a half. There is such a culture change not only being on campus but also being in a classroom again and the stakes are higher now than they were in college (financial investment and all that). Being able to acknowledge that no one really knows what lies ahead and still being willing to be a support system through anything is important and making sure students know that is even more important. School is already stressful but when you add heightened emotional stress and trying to get back to being in a more traditional setting there are definitely going to be setbacks. I think I'm most stressed about having to pretend this year is normal and everything is fine when in reality it's brand new and a lot is going on.

We're able to transfer to working remotely without too much struggle, and can travel to new places or to see friends and family without upending our schedules. SuccessfulLife_TEXT:
In my best case scenario, I imagine I'll probably be in my mid to late 40s and I'll have just completed a PhD in a field of math that I started to gravitate towards as an undergraduate. I'll have been keeping on top of my student loan payments long enough to feel comfortable with using my savings to make a down payment on a home with a fixed mortgage at a reasonable rate. My mental health would have its ups and downs, but I wouldn't need to put my whole life on pause for months or years every time I had a significant manic or depressive episode. I would maintain regular contact with my support network of friends, family, and medical providers.

To pay for grad school I'll have likely been working part-time in a field that requires a CompTIA certification at the least, but that values employees with college experience, under an employer that respects my goal to become a full-time researcher enough to accommodate my needs in that regard. Ideally, I would be making the transition into becoming an early stage career researcher between the final year of my master's degree program and the beginning of my PhD program. I would have a lot of work and school experience in and around math and computer science by this point and would be considered a respectable academic to my peers. Through credibility, research, and political action I could lend a more powerful voice to causes I care about.
SupportYou_TEXT: I'd be very grateful to the L&C faculty and staff if they could direct me towards academic opportunities that might give me a taste of what real scientific research is like. I'm looking for extracurricular activities like STEM clubs, undergraduate research projects, or even tutoring positions to get used to taking an active role in my education rather than just completing classwork.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: I am thinking that I will either go to grad school and progress to some kind of academic or academia-adjacent job, like writing, publishing, research, or even being a professor (the field of translation seems especially interesting to me because it combines multiple interests of mine), OR I’ll follow a path into a stem career in something like engineering or computer science. The first option is something that follows things I have enjoyed in the past (I’ve always liked reading and been a naturally pretty strong writer as well as an analytic thinker), and I think would work well with my intended philosophy major, but also with a different major in the humanities if I decide to switch to something else. The second option is something I’m not as sure whether I’d enjoy or not, because I don’t have much experience in the field, so it’s something I want to explore during college, maybe with internships but also just seeing how doing a math major goes. One thing is that I want to make a lot of money, and I know academia probably wouldn’t provide that, so I will definitely be making a life plan with that in mind, but at the same time I also want to be doing what I really love. Something that I have also always thought would be a dream job is something in music, for example a sound/score producer for movie soundtracks, but I’m just not sure I actually have the experience or skills to go into that professionally. However I guess I will talk to the career center at college and see if there are ways for me to explore that kind of career field--after all, I will probably end up having a minor in music or if not that I at least want to take a lot of classes. Interesting and horizon-broadening experiences, especially travel aka seeing different parts of the world is something really important to me that I want to follow in my adult life. That’s one of the reasons that making money is so important to me, but I also think if I could find internships and/or a job that allows me to work in various parts of the world for stretches of time, that would be ideal. I find languages fascinating and want to be a polyglot to engage in the cultures of many places regardless of what job I end up with. Finally, though building an interesting and fulfilling career is important to me, putting that aside, friends and having communities of people I spend time with is also vital to me in my life. I don’t see myself settling down with a partner and children or anything like that. Of course I want companionship in the future, but I see myself living in a city or multiple cities, having adventures with a group of friends. I know a lot of people tend to stop having as many friends or hobbies, or they just get busy and stop spending as much time with them as they get older, so it’s something I want to prioritize as I become an adult--making connections with people who are similar to me with similar interests and goals in life, and having not just one partner but a network of friends. I see myself without children continuing to partake in the things I enjoy like music, art, sports, reading and writing, or whatever else I am interested in, but the main thing is to continue having hobbies and varied interests and to find people I can engage with.

I want to participate in professor research while at college. I am also planning to take advantage of the career center to find internships or other opportunities relevant to my interests. Personally I find it very helpful when staff are willing to have a conversation outside of class, whether it’s about something I’m interested in exploring more or something I need help with.

SuccessfulLife_TEXT: Well if I am leading what I would consider a successful life, I would have been financially successful enough in the years prior that at the point in question I own property for one thing, and in general am comfortable, or insulated, or secure, or however you prefer to think of it. If I were leading a successful life, I would be involved in the areas of research which I find most important, namely taking control of the epigenetic changes implicated in the process of aging, i.e. "aging as a disease". I think that this area of research is what I need to contribute to in a meaningful way in order to feel I have led a successful life. If I feel satisfied in my work at some point down the line, it would have to be because, at least in part, I've made some meaningful contribution, expedited humanity's seizing control of ourselves and our physiology, scientifically and medicinally, and otherwise, et cetera. I think that in order to make such contributions I would need to be established one way or another academically, but I view this as a means to an end. It would undeniably be nice to be a fellow of such and such university, but I think accomplishments of the sort are not of primary concern.
